An underwater workout can be helpful for cats because the water supports their body weight while still providing gentle resistance, letting them move their joints and muscles without putting too much stress on them. 

This is especially useful for cats recovering from injuries, surgery, or arthritis, as it improves strength, balance, and flexibility while reducing pain and impact. The slow, controlled movement in water also helps rebuild muscle safely and can boost confidence in cats that are hesitant to move on land.

(Brita Kiffney, DVM, DABVP Canine And Feline Practice via ViralHog)

War Dogs is a 2016 dark comedy based on the true story of two young men who exploit a little-known government program that allows small businesses to bid on U.S. military contracts. Starring Jonah Hill and Miles Teller, the film follows their rise from living ordinary lives to making millions by supplying weapons to the U.S. Army during the Iraq War. As their success grows, so do the risks, moral compromises, and consequences of their actions. The movie blends humor with serious themes, highlighting greed, corruption, and the blurry line between ambition and irresponsibility. While entertaining and fast-paced, War Dogs also raises questions about ethics in war and how easily the system can be manipulated.

Straight-cut gears, commonly used in racing transmissions and older performance cars, differ from the helical gears found in most road vehicles. Instead of angled teeth, straight-cut gears have teeth that meet head-on, allowing for more direct power transfer with less friction and reduced axial load. This makes them more efficient under high-stress conditionsâideal for motorsports where durability and performance matter more than comfort.

But that performance comes with a signature sound: a loud, high-pitched whining or whirring noise that intensifies with speed. The sound is a result of the abrupt engagement between gear teeth, with no angling to smooth out contact. While impractical for daily driving due to noise and wear, itâs music to the ears of racing enthusiasts who know it signals a purpose-built machine.
